From: fjh@munta.cs.mu.OZ.AU (Fergus Henderson)
Subject: Re: set uid on scripts
Date: Sat, 30 Oct 1993 09:17:36 GMT

messina@netcom.com (Tony Porczyk) writes:

>Is it possible to set uid on shell scripts in Linux?  (Yes, security,
>I know).  It works nicely on BSD, you can even set it on SCO, but SCO
>will just ignore it when you try to execute the script (apparantly for
>security reasons, I am told).  How will it work on Linux?

Linux will ignore the setuid bit, just like SCO, because there are
a lot of easy ways to exploit setuid scripts.

I have a patch for Linux which fixes the security problem in the
kernel, and allows you to use setuid scripts, but you still need to be
*very* careful that there aren't any security problems in your shell or
your setuid shell scripts.

-- 
Fergus Henderson                     fjh@munta.cs.mu.OZ.AU

