From: pawel@cs.UAlberta.CA (Pawel Gburzynski)
Subject: Looking for recommendations regarding SCSI equipment
Date: Sat, 30 Oct 1993 01:56:11 GMT


I am going to buy some SCSI equipment for my Linux box and I would like to
hear from people who have similar setups. The list of the supported and 
unsupported controllers is more or less clear; however, there have been
numerous complaints regarding apparently supported but misbehaving pieces
of equipment.

At his moment I have a 486DX66/33 EISA motherboard with 16MB of memory,
256KB cache, two internal disks (250Mb each), and a GUS sound card. A few days
ago I visited my dealer and came up with the following possible additions:

      CTR SCSI ADAPTEC 1540C (ADP-71-0021 JB)
      HD 1.03GB SCSI2 Fujitsu (FJS-70-000 JB)
      TD 525M SCSI VIPER 2525S (MND-71-0006 JB)

Apparently, 1540C is supported by Linux at this time. I wonder if somebody
has been using the above (or a similar) equipment and can share with me
their experience. I am flexible and can buy anything in the price/capacity
range of the above items, thus I am very open for suggestions.

It seems to me that a publicly available list of configurations that various
people are using happily may be of enormous help to the newcomers who try to
build their boxes. Most traffic in the groups is related to problems, and
(quite understandably) nobody bothers to write that he/she is happy with
his/her setup. Owing to the diversity of the PC-compatible machinery, a
database of this sort may not be completely useless.

Thanks for your comments,

======================================================================
Pawel Gburzynski,
Department of Computing Science
University of Alberta, Edmonton, Alberta CANADA  T6G 2H1
e-mail: pawel@cs.ualberta.ca, tel: (403) 492-2347, fax: (403) 492-1071
